Drunken with corruption
My friend Boris was leaving my place, drunk.
I suggested he shouldn't drive.
He asked why.
"You've been drinking," I said, "aren't you afraid of the police?"
Boris me répondit : « non, je possède un document à l'effigie de Benjamin Franklin, ça rend toujours service ».
Il me montra son permis de conduire avec le billet de 100 dollars glissé à côté.
Évidemment, je savais que la police prend des pots-de-vin, mais je m'inquiétais que Boris rencontre un policier qui ne soit pas corrompu.
« Impossible », déclarait Boris, « pour entrer dans le corps de police affecté à la circulation, tu dois acheter le silence de ton chef.
Si tu ne prends pas de pots-de-vin, comment peux-tu acheter le silence de ton chef ?
The half of the drivers in Moscow use illegally bought driver's licenses.
The idiots who try to follow the rules get stuck in bureaucratic nonsense.
For 100 dollars, you can drive around town as if you're untouchable!
Corruption and embezzlement have always existed in Russia, before Lenin's October Revolution and after.
But never at the levels we see today.
Tout le monde accepte les pots-de-vin, partout et pour tout.
Les seuls qui n'en acceptent pas sont ceux à qui l'on n'en offre pas, selon Boris.
La corruption s'épanouit dans la plupart des institutions, et la lutte contre la corruption se finit toujours par une catastrophe ou un abandon.
La police, les procureurs, les douaniers et même le Kremlin : personne nulle part n'est immunisé.
Récemment, j'étais en visite dans un village de datchas dans l'une des plus jolies banlieues de Moscou.
This was a luxurious place but similar to a gulag with its high-security fences and guards.
Looking at the pretentious houses decorated with such poor taste, I wondered who owned them and was told that one belonged to an aide to the mayor of Moscow, another to a famous singer, and yet another to the son of the Moscow prosecutor.
But the most attractive property belonged to a modest tax official.
Corruption now represents a greater threat to Russia than the Chechen war.
In fact, the Chechen war would not have lasted as long if it had not been fought by corrupt generals, officers, officials, and police who sold weapons and supplies to the rebels.
The Russian TV showed recently a bus shuttling between Grozny and Moscow, the same bus that brought to Moscow the 120 kilograms of explosives used in the theater Dubrovka siege, where so many victims perished during the assault to free the hostages.
A passenger on the bus covered the explosives with a cloth soaked in acid to prevent the customs dogs from detecting them.
A precaution that was completely useless.
Noone controls the buses anymore today.
The driver who didn't know what he was transporting said he was stopped 50 times along his route, and for the same reason each time.
A policeman came asking him, "Do you know the price?" and the driver replied, "Of course, I know it," paying the bribe before leaving.
Without a bribe, the bus would have been delayed for hours at every stop, or entire days for the whole journey.
The war against Chechnya continues without end not only because Chechen rebels have allies like Al-Qaeda and the entire "international terrorism" but also because Russian corruption is their ally.
The police, the army, civilians who accept bribes, and thieves who first tax or simply steal from Chechen civilians, sell weapons and explosives to the terrorists, provide maps indicating where the minefields are, and supply the rebels with fake papers.
In May of this year, during the Kaspiisk explosions, the terrorists used weapons purchased from Russian army officers.
The rebels have modern weapons.
Where do they come from?
There are no gunshops in the mountains where the rebels hide.
But the 80,000 Russian soldiers fighting the rebels have ammunition stocks, from which the weapons are stolen and sold.
And not just weapons: some young officers sell their own men into slavery.
The corruption in Russia has reached catastrophic levels, and yet no battle has been launched against this evil.
To punish corruption more severely?
It would only increase the prices of corruption.
The harsher the punishment, the more one will have to pay to avoid it.
No official wants to fight corruption because they are corrupt themselves.
A thus, those called "the people" consider this phenomenon with benevolence.
They say of their mayor, "Yes, of course, he steals, but look at everything he has done for the city!"
Ordinary people also do not like honest workers.
Why?
A train ticket costs 100 rubles, but by giving a small bribe, one can travel for 50 rubles.
The traveler and the conductor both benefit from this system.
An honest old grandmother once told me that she bought a ticket and tried to board the train.
The conductor stopped her, saying that passengers with a ticket were not allowed on the train!
For millions of Russians, corruption is a normal way of life.
If you don't want your son to be called up for military service, buy an army clerk who will remove your son's name from the list or bribe a doctor to declare your son unfit for any military activity.
You can enter any university for a certain price, regardless of your references and diplomas.
You can drive drunk, speed, ignore red lights, as long as Benjamin Franklin is there to bribe the police.
Alexander Menchikov, minister under Peter the Great, understood the impossibility of winning the fight against corruption.
When the disgusted Tsar Peter decided to hang his corrupt officials, Menchikov replied: "Your Majesty, you risk losing all your subjects."
Since then, the situation has worsened over the centuries.
Removing corruption could leave the state without citizens, but if we do not stop the progress of corruption, citizens will soon be left without a state.
